text: Anyone spouting about childhoods being ruined needs to take a huge step back and watch the trailer again. What is honestly so different between this new movie, the 2003 cartoon, the 1990 movie, or the original comics? You. Any problem you have with this movie is really your own fault. Nitpicks, sure. Every movie has them. These turtles are huge and they have creepy lips. Whatever? They are still the same fun-loving brothers they always were. I've heard people say this new movie looks too grim and gritty..What. They are yukking it up all over the place! And even if it was overly grim and gritty, it would still just be that much more faithful to the source material. Just please take a step back and realize what it is that you're really complaining about. They aren't eating enough pizza? Come on. If you still have pains about this one movie in the entire history of TMNT, pop in your VHS tapes or read your trade paperbacks and keep on keeping on. Your childhood is absolutely fine.

text: I can't really understand the ire, as I actually like what I'm seeing. That's what the cartoon was, too; Silly looking mutant turtles spewing cringe-worthy one-liners between action scenes while trying to save a hot damsel-in-distress. Que in armies of brainless Foot Soldiers and other villains in good measure. The only thing 'off-rails' to me is the new Shredder, but who knows, perhaps he makes more sense in the context of the film.  While I'm still waiting for that bloody punk-tastic adaptation of the original self-published TMNT, this is likely the closest to the original cartoon we're going to get. Let's just hope the focus is on Turtles and not who-ever Will Arnett is playing (no offence to Arnett).

text: for those of you who seem to keep saying bay is only the producer of this film and not the director. here's a short definition of what movie producer role is  the producer is controlling everything... he provides all the equipment, promoting, publishing, he's paying and everything.... The director works according to the instructions of the producer. The producer gives him what it takes and the director should work by that.the producer also decide when the movie coming up.and the producer (or production company) gets the biggest income. It's like a gamble. the producer is the most important role in the creating of the movie.  that's part of the definitions of what a movie producer does guess whatÂ  i did to find it. i actually looked it upÂ  instead of blindly speaking so i'll sum it up what the definition means.. it means michael bay has more control of the film. he tells the director what to do and what he wants in the film. michael bay has control over the whole film. if the trailer isn't proof enough just by looking at the designs of the turtles. they look alien. shredder looks like a transformer. megan fox is april. o if your gonna use the turtles are mutants. what are mutant turtles suppose to look like. if the comics, animated cartoons, cgi movie, and live action movie doesn't show you . then your pretty much a casual fan at best. also just because their mutants doesn't mean they have to be 8ft tall and look like their on steroids. also here's another proof of michael bay having more say. read this part carefully. the trailer looks likeÂ  TRANSFORMERS.

text: To everyone flipping out, it really seems like you're just following the Michael Bay hate crowd and not forming your own intelligent opinions. Like one fellow said before, it's been nearly 30 years since the Turtles came out. They're still going strong (the new Nickelodeon series is great.) Of course, it's not going to be like the original cartoon, or the movies, or the source comics. This is a new adaptation, so it's going to differ from anything you've seen before. If it weren't, what point would there be in making it? It'd be redundant, so reserve your thoughts until after you've seen this new take on the heroes in a half shell. Be thankful they are back on the big screen at all, and in such a big way. The only thing that looks remotely ridiculous would be the overdone Shredder suit. A bit too knifey/bladey, but maybe there's a normal "form" before that. So, for those of you that bash this film, don't buy a ticket. text: Here's the problem I have with what I'm seeing here...  I feel like I've seen it before! Â All of this quick action, suddenly slow action, suddenly explosion, suddenly brutal body slam into some awkward inanimate object or window, suddenly witty line, suddenly back to quick action, slow action, flashing lights, and all of this being imitated by CGI... Â This style is being used so much these days. Â There doesn't seem to be anything new or fresh or risky here. Â Just an updated take on a story that just about everyone knows or is at least familiar with. Â   I love being entertained just as much as the next guy. Â But I'm also an intellectual, as well as a spiritual. Â I feel like there has to be some kind of honest substance (and I stress the word "honest"), otherwise I feel like I will leave the theater going, "yep, it was awesome, now what's for dinner?"

There's way more bad out there then good, and at this point it's easier to say that there were three good Star Wars movies, followed by thirty years of shit. text: I love the amount of slightly ignorant hate on here. TMNT is one of those odd fandoms (like James Bond actually) where people seem to forget the thing that made it popular (the late 80s cartoon in this case) is almost nothing like the source material. Yet, whenever a new version of the turtles appear people seem to keep referring to those cartoons simply because it's what made pop culture. Honestly, if you think about it, the original cartoons were basically the result of the comic creators "selling out" to make them kid-friendly.  Not saying this looks anything like the comics, hell no! However, it doesn't look as horrible it could have been so I'm gonna give it a shot. Yes the character designs are not exactly great, but everyone hated Heath Ledger's "grunge" Joker look, then suddenly most didn't care after his performance.

text: Shut the fuck up with all of your bitching about it ruining your childhood.Â  Seriously. Its a new take on,Â quite honestly, a played out story.Â I had EVERYTHING as kid related to ninja turtles. text: People, JONATHAN LIEBESMAN IS THE DIRECTOR, Bay is the producer. The TMNT franchise has known several major incarnations, so there are some significant differences already: http://turtlepedia.wikia.com/wiki/Comparisons_within_Teenage_Mutant_Ninja_Turtles  The ORIGINAL TMNT come from Mirage comics. The comic book really wasnâ€™t made for kids, they were filled with graphic violence, including blood spray, stabbings and ritualistic suicide. But when Playmates Toys expressed interest in producing TMNT action figures in 1986, the comicâ€™s PG-13 attitude wouldnâ€™t fit Playmates' 4-8 year old target audience. In addition, part of Playmatesâ€™ marketing was an animated cartoon, which had to pass television censors. So to make the Turtles viable for children, the Turtles had to soften up.  source: http://mentalfloss.com/article/30862/complete-history-teenage-mutant-ninja-turtles  There you have it, before bashing anything, at least know what you're talking about. The cartoon from the 80's changed many things from the original TMNT comics, it was dumbed down for kids, you could say it was the first "rape" of the turtles. The live action movies have been very mediocre so far and this one seems ready to join the club, but time will tell.

text: People need to stop being haters. I feel this movie will probably be a C. But this is the FIRST live action movie since the ones in the 90's. I'm excited to see some of my most nostalgic characters from my childhood on the big screen. The 4 turtles are fine by me, I like their animation, their voices, their personalities, and everything. A little less on Donatello if I had a gripe. Shredder looks crazy, and the only thing that I think will be able to give us a good fight against these massive turtles. Shredder also looks pretty fantastic himself. Some of the jokes and dialogue feel quirky (reminiscent of transformers saga) but thats just the way he does his films. The worst part of this is megan fox. She doesnt act her scenes well, and I think a redhead would have been better suited for this role. I wont bag on her too bad because I find her very attractive in a sexual way. Anyway here'es my input and me and my 3 year old son are going to go see this movie, probably opening day :D

text: I wonder how people would react if Michael Bay's name wasn't attached to this movie. Would people still say they're ruining the turtles? I feel like since his name is attached, everything is under a microscope. And what exactly are they ruining? If you see the movie and don't like it, you could still go back and watch the cartoon whenever you please. It's not like it'll disappear from all existence when the movie comes out. Did "Batman and Robin" disappear when "Batman Begins" came out? No, it's still there, but the animated series and everything else Batman is still here. T his movie isn't "ruining your childhood," it's just using the same characters. And don't say you hope this movie sucks! Why would you want that?! Fans of the turtles should hope that this movie is awesome, not trash on it!

text: I think sizable problem is an over mechanized Shredder as shredder was always a bit more human outside of the radical... gnarly, experimental stunts.  But the main major one for me is the total different personality around the turtles in their speaking. They had a cool more beach bum youthful voice (of ignorance) like that of the west coast cliche while Splinter was a very much Asian-style wise teacher. I didn't really get that but more of a ghetto urban, hipster style behavior. I guess more fitting for modern New York, but just not that quirky funny thing about it that was highly attractive.  I think they just applied the Hollywood formula of throwing money at it for making it a visual spectacle instead of putting a well thought, DEEP story into it. I don't mind the high action, exaggeration visuals of modern Hollywood though, I just hate the ignoring of committing to great original plots, character stories and overall storytelling quality.  That's what I get form this. At the very least in positive regards, it doesn't look like it'll be a total blow of movie. I think the Original Ninja turtles movie did right exactly where this movie lacks.

text: Really? People are defending this? I'm all for new ideas, but not if it butchers the source material. And I know the concept of mutant ninja turtles is already out there, but come on this is ridiculous!   All the goofy clothing and accessories look cluttered. Shredder's design looks like it was done by a twelve year old (we get it, he's Shredder, he doesn't need 100 blades sticking out everywhere though). The Foot Clan uses guns now, because that's apparently what ninjas do in 2014. And why does every main character have to be CGI?? If they could pull off suits and puppets over 20 years ago, imagine what they could do today. But instead we get Teenage Mutant Transformers with Magneto/Megatron Shredder and Megan Fox doing her permanent O-face in every reaction shot.   I know TMNT has always been campy, but there is such a thing as subtlety people. At the end of the day they're suppose to be ninjas (from the turtles to Shredder and the Foot), and NONE of them look, feel or act like ninjas. This trailer is just a bunch of loud noises, explosions and dubstep. If you can get excited for that, more power to you. But don't bitch about other people who don't like the way this film looks. We have just as much right to hate on it as you do to love. We clearly have valid reasons for "hating". After all it's our money that we're potentially wasting to go see this crap.

text: You got to applaud the 'strategy' used to market this film. Paramount and Bay's team intentionally mislead us right from the beginning in order to lower our expectations. They lead us to believe that 1.) William Fichtner will play Shredder and 2.) The Turtles are from alien origin (I'm sure there were more.) By later revealing simple things that are inherent to the original Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles story (Oroku Saki IS Shredder and Turtles' mutagenic origin), they have locked in some of the first skeptics and die-hard fans, and most of us are praising what really are simple 'facts' in TMNT lore... Well played, indeed.

text: Back in the 80's, the once proud comic series Ninja Turtles was dragged by Fox Kids into an abyss of shame. And today, most people remember Ninja Turtles for the cheesiness, stupid catchphrases, pizza, annoying voices and comedic action. Bay is keeping them on that course.  It was not always like this. There was a time, when the Ninja Turtles did NOT have multi-colored, masks, or have catchphrases, ate pizza, talked like morons and only used their weapons for defence. In that time, they all wore red masks, did not say cowabunga, ate Chinese food instead of Pizza, talked like people raised in a Ninja Clan, and used their weapons not just to defend, but also stab, slash, cut, break bones and kill.  I want a Ninja Turtles movie based on the original comic books written by Peter Liard and Kevin Eastmen. The 80's cartoon had it's fun, but the 80's are over. I say it's time to return the turtles to their roots as stealthy, deadly warriors who strike hard from the shadows, and then fade into the night.

text: OK i gotta say it, first off im a complete fan girl for TMNT, i grew up with them but seeing the things they added in the movie is going to ruin it for me. Donatello may be the smart one of the group but adding all of the high-tech gear just doesn't look good (Donny is my favorite character). Ralph's mask differs from the other brothers (looks more like a bandanna), and Shredder killed the movie, He is a excellent villain but they made him look like a robot instead of a Samurai. Give the movie props since the attitude and personality they kept on each character. Leo being Serious and Dedicated, Donny being Intelligent, Mike being Carefree and Crazy, and Ralph being Angry and Aggressive. Megan Foxx, a good actor, but i could see Scarlett Johansson playing April much better than her. Also the turtles look like the are at last 25, i'm assuming the word "Teenage" means nothing to Micheal Bay Overall I want to watch this movie because its practically mandatory for a Ninja Turtle fan but I don't see it getting rated more than at least a 4.0 out of 5.0 stars. Don't get mad at this comment because we all have our opinions.

text: In 1989 I was given my first Ninja Turtle action figure (Donatello). It was while on a trip across the country in NY. At the time I couldn't believe such a cool idea could even exist.I grew up with the cartoons and when the movie hit, they just got even better. Most everybody can say they were THE biggest turtle fan, but I really was. I collected nearly every action figure till about the mid 90's and loved the video games. Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  I watched this trailer and that little kid in me, who loved the ninja turtles, just died. The Hollywood rape machine just keeps getting stronger. A batman reference, A personality that says "super creepy" like a teenage girl would, A shredder that looks and sounds like a transformer (go figure), The Foot-clan using machine guns and driving around in pimped out escalade's and hummers. bad voice acting and CG turtles (really?). Humor that is just awful and I do mean horribly awful. Everybody has their opinions on things, who really cares. But, if you think this is a good thing, you are definitely part of the problem. I haven't set foot in a theater in years, and after seeing this trailer I am pretty sure I never will again. It is most definitely going to get worse from here. I bet this piece of shit will even do well at the box office and see a sequel. I will be proud to say that I did not contribute in any way. Farewell, Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles (Hero's in a half shell) TURTLE POWER!

text: Who the hell are entertainment products like this one aimed at? If you're not making it like the comics, then you are not trying to appeal to its fans. How does it make sense to waste a franchise title by making it only for audiences outside the fanbase? Because that's all that is happening. You make a product unrelated to franchise X, for audience Y, and use the name of franchise X. The name has no impact on the reception by audience Y, and the absent quality only has impact on the reception by audience X. It's literally a 100% failure on all fronts. Everyone loses, especially the franchise itself.

Your franchise is called "Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles". The premise is already silly by default. I mean seriously, what were you expecting?  People whining about the Shredder? I would have to assume that much of the people whining here are far more nostalgic for the 80s cartoons and seem to have forgotten how stupid that adaptation of the comic was. Shredder was more of a petulant, whiny Saturday morning antagonist like so many others in the 80s instead of a proper villain. If you're complaining about his ethnicity, they already confirmed him to be Asian. In fact, this is being directed by the very people responsible for your "childhood" in the first place

text: The movie actually looks good so far, and that's saying something for a Michael Bay movie(I know he's not the director this time, but don't forget, he was the one with that stupid idea to change the Turtles' backstory from mutated turtles to aliens, which got scrapped).  I'm tired of trailers spoiling a lot though. They didn't show The Shredder's face, which is good, and I like The Shredder's armor, looks badass &Â it makes sense, people actually use guns in this Ninja Turtles movie, it best to have armor. In fact, it makesÂ perfectÂ sense that the Foot Clan uses guns, this Ninja Turtles movie is set in Modern Day,Â think how easily the Turtles could've been taken out in the original films if even one Foot Ninja had a gun.  I like the Turtles' new looks, especially Donatello's, the voices fit each character, especially the voice for Raphael. I must say, the TurtlesÂ & Splinter being CGI, its a lot better than Animatronics. I liked the original films, 1 & 2 anyway, not 3, as much as the next person, but its clear those Animatronics wouldn't work nowadays, CGI is the best choice, and it will nice to see Splinter kicking ass just like it was good to see Yoda kick ass.  The actor playing Shredder in this is white, which does suck, but think about this, remember in Iron Man 3, the person who we thought was The Mandarin, really wasn't The Mandarin. Well, what if that's the case here? This Shredder isn't the real Shredder, but someone Oroku Saki wants people to believe is Shredder, so if he gets caught, Oroku Saki could be elsewhere with a backup plan, maybe they show is face after the end credits. This a *big* What-if, but after what happened with The Mandarin in Iron Man 3, I wouldn't be surprised if something similar happened here.  It still baffles me why the hell Megan Fox of all people, was picked for the role of April O' Neil, they didn't even make her a redhead in this. I'll admit, the part where she faints after seeing the Turtles is funny, but, any other actress would've been a better choice.
author: TheGameKeeper94

text: Can people stop complaining about how this movie is gonna suck? I will admit, at first I didn't like what I was seeing. The accessories, the way the characters look, Megan Fox, and the foot pretty much being terrorists. But I'll tell you one thing. You can't just look at a trailer and call a movie terrible *except for Twilight* Here are good things about this movie. Michael Bay is just the producer, the turtles still have their personalities, Splinter looks adorable, good chance of Oroku Saki being in it at 1:15, the're not aliens, *They even made fun of that at the end*, still some good jokes in the movie instead of being all dark, and lastly the TMNT are being the TMNT. That's it. No reason to hate on this movie besides the things I listed at the beginning of this. So everyone who says this is gonna suck just by looking at this trailer, give it one more chance. And if you don't like what you see on the big screen just complain to me about it,

text: Ok let's be completely honest here. What is the first thing that comes to mind when you think of ninja turtles in general? Seriously just think. It's something around the lines of turtles fighting shredder or the krang while chilling and eating pizza. Visually you probably pictured them as the 90's cartoon or the original Jim Henson animatronics. Whatever version you thought about it pretty much defines who they are. If you're going to pull the old "this is true to the original comics that were dark and gritty" card out you have to take into account that not many people knew about the original ninja turtle comic's at all. Hell those were printed in cheap newspaper esque material and are really rare to find nowadays.   The ninja turtles in their peak were a commercialized wet dream. After the comics they became the turtles we know today. A lot of interpretations deviated from the original comics but they kept the recurring principle of cheesy jokes, over the top villains, pizza appetite and the overall design they shared from the 90's cartoon. It was the identity that everyone knew them as. And even the new Nickelodeon show stays true to these aspects. So it stands to reason that an ultimate brute redesign like this would spur the fans out.  I'm still keeping an open mind to watch this film but my only real gripe is that the characters and the story itself just doesn't look interesting at all. Just another generic action flick

text: Lets be honest haters, It's extremely difficult to take something as silly as mutant humanoid turtles from a cartoon show, and make it photo realistic without encountering problems in the original design. In animation, it's easier to make the designs look natural when compared to everything around them, Most residents of NYC in the show are normal humans, of course, and the turtles are not. But because it's a cartoon, the features of many normal humans are exaggerated, and therefore look unrealistic, and therefore don't look out of place when they encounter the turtles. In regards to the turtles themselves, because they are animated, there are certain details you can get away with not showing. For example, because live action often has to look photorealistic with live action cg creations, there are more details that can be, and often must be, shown on a cgi creation, such as sweat, the movement of their bandanas against their bodies etc. In animation(More specifically the 87 series) you don't really see scales on the turtles, and as a result it just looks like green skin, and the sweat is often just big cartoonish sweat beads. The turtles in the new movie definitely look jarring and out of place next to the humans, as well as their 87 designs, but that's the point, they are meant to look out of place and strange because they ARE out of place and strange. and I can still recognize who they are, both in look and in personality. Raph seems like Raph, Donatello seems like Donatello and so on.  I don't see the problem here in all honesty, and for those who want to explain to me why they don't like it, feel free, I like discussion and debate, just, as a point of challenge, explain it to me without mentioning your pessimism due to Michael Bay's involvement, and tell me if you would hate it as much if he had nothing to do with the production of the film. text: I loved the 1987 cartoon. It was the cartoon I grew up with. It had the best theme song, the best toys, the best characters, just everything about that cartoon was awesome. It finally got cancelled sometime in '96 or '97. Then came that live action show that the people that did Power Rangers produced which... sucked. Then came that dark cartoon in 2003 that... sucked. Then that TMNT computer animated movie came out and that SUCKED!!! Finally we get this stupid show that Nickelodeon makes and they just totally butcher it! I mean Donatello has buck teeth, and a crush on teenage April not to mention Rob Paulsen the guy who was the original voice for Raphael in the original cartoon does his Donatello's voice while Sean Ass-Ton! does Raphael's. Michelangelo has acne or something, and the cool catch phrases like "Turtle Power" and "Cowabunga" are no longer the phrases they use... I hate Nickelodeon seriously. People can hate this all they want, but I am just a big fan of the 1987 cartoon.

text: I'm probably one of the biggest TMNT fans ever since I was little. When I came to America this was the first TV cartoon I watched. My first birthday in America was TMNT themed. I still remember the birthday song followed by all my friends singing the original TMNT theme song. Regardless of all the hate and the "changes" in the backstory and the look of these characters I feel there may be some good things here. Maybe the heart of the characters are still in tact. I don't know. No one knows. How about we judge the movie when it actually does come out?Â Â I'm going to give it a shot. I'm psyched they are actually making the movie in the first place. Not everyone realizes how much money and effort it takes to create a movie. With so many people's creative input we often fail to realize that it should not all fall onto one man. I'm not a big Michael Bay fan like many of my peers here. But if he hits this one out of the park I will definitely think differently of him.Â

text: Ok I'm sorry but you have to realize how terribly bootleg the original concept it originally was... You're telling me... 4 turtles mutated by green ooze learned martial arts from a mutated rodent who learned those martial art techniques from his owner and were named after renaissance artists and sculptors each with distinct personalities and they gorge on pizza sound like a good time? Do you remember how just plain silly the Jim Henson variants were? The Foot were profiting off stolen VHS's, NYC never had complaints of a hocky masked street fighter, and in the 90's cartoon they went through practically a series involving time travel. I grew up watching those films and looking back... they are pretty damn bootleg. Give them credit for awesome costume designs and sure it's in cgi but obviously they didn't want to pull a "Grinch" and make grown men look like Whos in this film. Point and case is this. YES this is designed for a new generation. YES the casting could be better. Yes there is CGI for things that obviously normal actors can't do. That avalanche/snow chase? This isn't Lone Survivor wear people in turtle outfits can be tumbling down in... This is coming from one of the guys who really didn't like Transformers and other films that "ruin" the childhood. Sure, yes,Transformers really didn't need 2 scenes of dogs humping each other let alone have a transformer insistent to hump Megan Fox's leg. As far as I can tell they don't have that kind of crude humor in this film. From the guy who said "this looks fucking stupid" when it was trailed. I'm willing to take my kid sister to see this. Why? She'll like the pop culture references. She wouldn't get the Caesco (pardon the error) bat jokes from TMNT 1990... Sure I wish the design was moooore... turtle-ish but it still looks something similar to the 90's cartoons I'd bum up and watch with my dad on Saturday mornings. Sure I wish the Foot didn't seem like a PMC group but nevertheless it's still the disgusting bootleg thing I remember. I'm sorry you can't argue a "pepperoni and ice cream pizza" from the first episode of the 1987 series. Point and case is, if you think this looks weird take a LONG gander at the franchises history. Will it be the best TMNT's for older fans? Hell no. But will it provide something similar that the coming generation will comprehend? Yes. I may be 18 but it's kinda hard to forget owning the series on VHS and collecting the figurines as a kid.

text: When I saw the first trailer, I was quite disappointed. I've been a Turtles fan since decades and was really angry to see their appearance. But now I feel they look quite amazing! This trailer is fantastic (and the others released after the first trailer). In the previous TMNT movies, I think the the Turtles were made to look how they appeared in the cartoons and comics. But here, they look realistic. Â But still quite some complaints though, namely: 1) Shredder. He was a japanese guy. Here, he's an american. Plus, he seems to rely heavily on high-tech armor for fighting Â rather than martial skills.Â  2) April o Neil. Megan fox has lost her charm. She was in her "prime" during "Transformers" (no pun intended) but now she's not that attractive. Even she doesn't have the characteristic red hair that April has. Even the little bit of acting that we see from Megan in the trailers doesn't remind you of the April we know. 3) The costumes of Turtles are bit ridiculous, except for Leonardo's. Maybe the other three also could have similar costumes. 4) The foot soldiers seem to be gun-totting hoodlums, not ninjas. But still, I'm VERY desperately waiting for the movie to release!

text: It's funny how absurd people bitching about this film are. First, it feels like it's the cool thing to hate Michael Bay. Most of the people are saying he blows just because that's what the cool kids are doing. I'm not a Michael Bay fan but, as far as special effects driven blockbuster directors go, he's average in the worst case and most of his films have been commercial succeses, so he must be doing something right (at the end of the day, making lots of money is the main goal for this type of movie, this is not some artistic indie experimental film or a movie to take consideration for the oscars. Another thing, MICHAEL BAY ISN'T DIRECTING He's one of the SIX producers of the film. The quality of the film is about 95% directing AND screenplay, both of wich Michael Bay has nothing to do with. Lastly, GROW THE FUCK UP, this isn't ruining your memories from 1900's TMNT with the Vanilla Ice soundtrack, and if it is the dont fucking watch it. Simple as that. Nobody, let alone studios, give a fuck about your nostalgia. Times change, technology change, people change, markets change. 1900's TMNT wouldn't succeed this day and age, so they have to make a movie made for this era. And also, do you really think that if you were to watch the 1900's TMNT for the first time being an adult you would actually enjoy it? The only reason people enjoy those old films now is because it takes them back. They bring good memories and nostalgia. So stop fucking complaining. Don't watch it if you are so butthurt but let life and the cicle of popula culture run its inevitable curse.

Almost like Vin Diesel kind of acting! The movie was funny as hell, EVERYONE was fucking funny! But man Mikey was too funny! Leo was a Great fucking leader and you could tell the turtles respect him, Donnie was too good too lol! Incredibly well played and actually had some great moments to shine! Ralph was a stubborn badass and his speech at the end was incredible! Master Splinter was my favorite character, You could tell he loved his sons, and they loved him too! His fight vs Splinter was too damn good! GOD I love this movie. I honestly dont know what to say about its that bad.l..Megan Fox's acting? It was ok, the best yet from her...but everything else was too good! sure they changed the story a bit, but so do tons of other movies, Nolan's batman. Wolverine...I could go on! BUT THIS MOVIE WAS FUCKING GREAT and the action scenes were superb...did I say this movie was hilarious?? 9/10! FUCKING LOVED IT!

text: I just went to see this last night with the Mrs. and we had a LOT of fun. We've been TMNT fans for 25 years now, and we agreed that if we didn't want to watch Guardians of the Galaxy so much, we'd have no problem with paying to see TMNT again next week when we go out.  To the people who "know it's going to be bad" without knowing anything about it- Trust me when I say that this trailer is VERY misleading. This trailer does NOT do the movie any justice whatsoever.Â   In fact, it is very evident that Bay aimed this movie towards the older TMNT fans and not the kids of today that haven't really followed TMNT so long. In the theater, there were mostly couples and spouses in their 30s, mostly all wearing old school ninja turtles t-shirts. It was a great time.  There are many homages to the original 1990 movie in this new one. Do yourself a favor and DON'T listen to any hype off the internet where everyone hates everything just for the sake of having something to say. Go see this movie, you will have a good time.

text: This movie is terrible.Â  And it's not terrible because they changed the look of the turtles, or made minor changes to their backstory.Â  Its terrible because they made major changes to their backstory that don't make sense, and because Megan Fox is boring as hell onscreen, and is made the focus of the film, and it's hero in many ways.Â  April O'Neil is not the hero.Â  She is not the daughter of a brilliant scientist.Â  The turtles don't owe their very lives to her, and her father did not name them.Â  This movie reads like a Mary Sue fanfic.Â  Is it so hard to believe that a reporter that had NOTHING to do with the turtles until they emerged from the sewers could befriend them?Â  Why the hell does there need to be some big stupid reveal about how she was there and involved with them from the very beginning?Â  How is that realistic?Â  And why the hell is Shredder treated like a generic bad guy and given no chance to develop his character at all?Â  This whole thing is just stupid, and I say that as someone who actually ENJOYED the Transformers movies.Â  Sure, they had their flaws, they weren't true to the character's designs.Â  But at least Sam and his parents antics were funny to watch.Â  This film has no heart. It's just terrible. And I can't believe a sequel has already been greenlighted.

text: I grew up with the cartoon and I must say that this was a pretty good movie. I enjoyed the filmmaker's take on the TMNT lore. One disappointment is that they had the Oroku Saki (Shredder) act like a Joel Schumacher-like Bane, and not the genius villain mastermind with an awesome backstory. Shredder is one of the greatest villains of all-time! He can't be degraded to a big bulky robot with no personality! But I really like how they spot-on conveyed each turtle's personality! Raph was such a badass and Donnie easily was my favorite. Also, Splinter didn't learn from Hamato Yoshi (who wasn't even in this alternate reality's lore), but Splinter learned Ninjitsu from a book?! Anyway, I'm guessing with the right writing, the sequel will be better with a bigger and better concentration on Shredder (who obviously wasn't killed).

author: Franz Lafienova

text: I have never been a fan of the Ninja Turtles. I watched the first few movies, and I just disliked them straight off the bat. And I don't normally hate Superheroes.... But I wanted to be fair. I wanted to give this movie a chance. I saw the movie a few days ago... And it was, honest to God, one of THE WORST movies I have ever seen in my life. I didn't like the Turtles before this movie. And now I just despise them. They looked horrible in this movie. It was like looking at Dr Eggman in Sonic the Hedgehog 2006. It just wasn't right.  People may hate this, but I'm gonna say it.... They suck as superheroes. Just watching them get their asses kicked in this movie was just painful to watch. They are the worst group of Action Heroes I have ever seen in my life. Only 2 characters did I give half a shit about: Will Arnett's character, and Splinter. To me, there were the only vaguely interesting. And they barely did anything in this movie.  Christ, I didn't even like the first 2 Ninja Turtles movies... But I'd watch them any day over this movie.  But I know what some people are going to say. "You can't judge this movie properly because you're not a major Ninja Turtles fan!"  Well, the person I saw this movie with, my girlfriend, just happens to be a Ninja Turtles fan. She's probably watched all the Ninja Turtle movies and cartoons out there.... And even she hated this movie. She was literally stunned silent at the end. And not in a good way.Â   Bottom Line: This movie sucked for me. One of the worst movies I've ever seen. Right up there with Walking With Dinosaurs on the level of suckitude.  The plot was boring and all over the place. The backstory to the Turtles and Splinter was uninteresting. The other characters are uninteresting. The turtles looked horrible. They suck at fights, and protecting civilians. They suck at humor (Only one of their lines in this movie was vaguely hilarious). They are painful and embarassing to watch whenever they're in action. Never again will I watch this movie.  Honestly.... you know what? Fuck the Ninja Turtles. They are simply the worst. I didn't like the first Avengers movie.... And yet I'd rather watch that. Or the Power Rangers. Or Superman. Or Hancock. Or any other Superhero

text: Just saw this movie, and as someone who grew up watching the 1987 series i was kinda dissapointed. It didnt seem as bad to me as most people make it out to be, the action scenes was decent and the dialogue/relationship (interplay?) between the turtles was good, but thats about it.Â  Splinter looked super creepy and became an expert ninja from reading a 50 page manual, for some reason the turtles are now hulk like and bullet proof, shredder is basically iron man and the foot clan ninjas are just common gun slinging mercenaries. I get that donatello is the tech guy, but his tech was too futuristic like holograms in his wrist and an iron man display in his goggles, the sexual attention from mikey was over the top, and i am really tired of Megan Fox, cant remember a movie ive seen with her that made me think "Damn, she really carried that movie, she is so talented!". All in all ive deffinately seen worse films, andÂ atleast it wasnt as big a slap in the face to the fans of original content as the dragon ball movie was :) (And i know the 1987 series is not actually the original content, but still)

text: This really is a love it or hate it kind of movie, so let's chalk them up against each other IN A MASSIVE REVIEW. (SPOILERS YO):  LOVED: The action scenes. Say what you want about Bay, but he knows how to make them cool. Ninja badassry everywhere, with a notable lack of pointless explosions. The characterisation of the turtles. They kept the teenage tenancies (like the beatboxing) in there as well as their base personalities most reminiscent of the 2003 series and the 1990 first movie and as always provided a slightly different interpretation in how to present them. They're still the turtles we love guys. Arnett's acting. It was amongst the best in the film, and it was a pleasant surprise seeing the character of Vernon return after over a decade.Â    HATED: Fox's acting. She rarely had an array of expressions or emotion in her voice, so when she did actually act it felt out of place and awkward for the thus far emotionless character with nothing but her obsession for reporting going for her. She wasn't over-sexualised in this movie like transformers (thank god), but there was also generally too much focus on her in the first third of the movie in order to make the plot go forward, when we just wanted to see more of the turtles. The Shredder's and Karai's average villian treatment. Sacks is given a lot more development and focus than shredder, which makes old bucket-breath seem like he was just slapped in there, no matter how cool his armour ended up being. Karai as well is just a chick who commands the mooks, whereas in other incarnations she's almost always on equal or greater footing in ninja skills than the turtles, so it's disappointing we never saw her fight. The Foot in general. So they're not a super secret ninja clan with a respectful public face, but rather a modern crime organisation hell bent on money. WITH GUNS. And they're WELL KNOWN. How they even do stuff without getting caught is anyone's guess.Â    UNSURE: The edited origin. So they were laboratory experiments that purposely mutated them instead of the (frequently) accidental creation via alien substances. In this respect it's similar to the IDW comics (made after nick's purchase of the turtles), so it wasn't completely new. You can always say the original origin is the best, but this origin does give the turtles a bigger connection to April.Â  Splinter not being Hamato Yoshi. Well in the 2003 series he's just a super intelligent (and ordinary) rat that learned ninjutsu by watching Yoshi before he got mutated, so the fact that in this his mutated self learned it by reading books is in a way marginally more believable. It would have been possible to have Yoshi as part of the laboratory professors, but then you gotta answer why he's in america, whether he has a connection to the shredder, how he got mutated when the turtles got mutated by injection and so on. So for the sake of the plot that they chose, it works.Â  The turtle's design and choice of motion capture. They either look awesomely realistic for humanoid turtles, with their unique builds like the 2012 series and personalised clothing. OR they look a bit too deep into the uncanny valley to be lovable and basically grotesque. You can't win. Whilst I personally also found their designs something I had to get used to, by the end of the movie I quite liked all the little details they added like Donnie's tech stuff, Raph's scar on his shoulder and the paint on Mikey's shell, and being able to have those wonderful expressions on their faces was a treat. The acting of the turtles MC and voice acting was pretty good overall too, but if there was more focus on them individually (character-wise) throughout the movie it'd be easier to draw a conclusion.Â    CONCLUSION: It's Marmite guys. You can either love the movie for what it is: an action flick with cool action about our turtles as themselves and enjoy the new interpretation in our massively varied canon. Or you can hate the designs, the villian's treatment and the familiar but unoriginal story. But in any viewpoint, it's got the privilege of not being horrendously awful OR the next blockbuster. Which way it goes on the Average Scale is up to you, but hey, at least they're not aliens.

text: As a fan of the TMNT since they first came out waaay back in 1984, I dislike the movie and I'll tell you why.  rating them  Teenage Mutant Ninjas Turtles 1990- great humor. Just enough of a dark theme, humor and action to not make it corny. Also liked the chosen live actors. Hoag (April), Jones (Koteas), Saito. (The Shredder), Turney. (Danny), and even Serra (Chief Sterns). Didn't need BIG STARS to make a good movie A+   Teenage Mutant Ninjas Turtles 2: Secret of the Ooze (1991):  Good sequel.  Wished there was a little more action in the film but unfortunately since ppl complained about the violence in part one the director filled it full of wisecracks. Liked the attempt to do an origin story. Wish Eastman and Laird would've let the director put Bebop and Rocksteady in this movie instead of two equally dumb mutants. Could've done with Vanilla Ice's "Ninjas Wrap" Turbo was an ok replacement for Hoag, Reyes Jr. got a little annoying at times with his one liners...Tochi,Carl, and Faso weren't as good voicing Leonard,  Donatello, and Raph as the voice actors from the original movie. The animatronic turtles from the original were better, but these are A WORLD better than part 3.  Solid B   Teenage Mutant Ninjas Turtles 3: Lets start with the animatronic suits. They looked AWFUL. Henson studios didn't do them, so they look lie frog-turtle bad costumes. The past storyline could've worked IF they didn't make the entire thing like a feel good PG 13 , snappy snorefest.  It was a God attempt to bring back Elias Koteas, who really was in it just to be seen....but rarely used. Instead played an awful ancestor??? Overall it was the worst out of the series,  YES EVERYONE even worse than the remake.  This gets an F  TMNT (2007): I had hope for this until I had heard the AWFUL idea to split up the turtles. YES Raphael and Leonardo have butted heads but Splinter would never let this happen.  Then you don't even add a villain such as The Krang,  Leatherhead, Baxter Stockman ex.... but a millionaire and some old warrior as a villain?  Didn't like it. The only thing that was good, is the voice acting. My favorite was Mikey, voiced by Mikey Kelly.  I got a kick out of him and even though they turned Raph into a vigilante knight from hell...Noland North was a decent Raphael ans well as Taylor as Leonardo, Iwamatsu as Splinter and Evans as Casey Jones. Gellar to me...didn't sound like she fit April's tough but from attitude. .. just like Buffy doing an impersonation.  Rate this a C+  Teenage Mutant Ninjas Turtles (2014): Uhh, were do I start?  They looked hideous.. and for some reason we're only slightly taller in other versions it in this their 8 or 9 feet tall!? Then you have Bay's desperate attempt to fill this with well known actors to hopefully sell this movie.  You have horrible actress Megan Fox for sex appeal ( that's all she's good for), Will Arnett. ( who just seemed aqward and out of place) and Whoopi Goldberg -- in a flashback to 1992 as Bernadette Thompson (what? They turned Bern. Thompson from the cartoon into a black woman.  DOES THAT MAKE SENSE?) . The origin story was boring and weak, The Shredders armor was too over the top ( they got it right in part one and two bot to mention the cartoons. Is it that hard to. ... you MORONS!!!), cheap gags to cover up the plot holes, and just Michael Bay's SAD attempt to rejuvenate the franchise.  I'm glad I rented this instead of paying 8.00 to see this plane crash.  I rate this a D- only because TMNT 3 was a bit worse in my eyes.

text: as a Turtles fan from way back I gotta say this movie is CRAP. I, like everyone seen the previews and thought the CGI turtles look God awful but I wanted to see for myself if i'm  just judging it unfairly so I watched it...BIG MISTAKE.    I know a lot of ppl who like this movie defend their look but they didn't look like turtles... they looked like a half human hybrid... and ugly as hell.  to the ppl who say that real turtles actually have lips,  nostrils ex... these is a fictional based turtles And in EVERY incarnation,  none of the ninja turtles  have human facial features so stop with that bullcrap.   the plot was awful.  they focused too much on April...and when they did get to the plot, the origin story was weak. the whole " April was their pet/turtles angle" was a desperate attempt  to connected the five characters (April and the turtles) to move the story along. You can't forget the irony of how she happens to be there when they are and how TRAINED NINJAS can't seem to stay hidden. can't forget the plot to destroy the city. ..release a deadly toxin....wait? didn't they do that in an Amazing Spider-Man or Batman Begins?  way to use new material Michael Bay...dip sh*t!!!!!  then you got the equally bad Megan Fox as April. She's so bad and unbelievable in this, you were better off putting a guy in a wig to play her.   There suppose to be basing this off the 1985 cartoon ( why else would they have Burn Thompson,  Vernon, and in the sequel Bebop & Rocksteady)...so why doesn't April have light brownish red hair? Then there's the horrible dialogue.  Leo tells April stop following them or "we will find you" which was creepy enough but then Michaelangelo makes it worse by repeating the dialogue...And sounding like a psychotic stalker  and how about turning April's boss from the series into a woman?  WHAT? And on top of it you cast Whoopie Goldberg who's been irrelevant in films for two decades.  then finally these so called Ninjas (which. are trained by the best in Splinter) get their a**es kicked in most of the movie.  aren't they supposed to be well trained martial artist?  my suggestion. ...watch the 1990 film. it was fun, had just enough dark humor and some great fun lines action and fight scenes.  Don't see or rent this piece of garbage.

text: Okay I'm tired of people talking crap about Michael Bay and his movies. You do realize that Kevin Eastman and Peter Laird were there during the production of this film and they personally liked the way how Michael Bay created this movie. Plus TMNT are humanoid turtles they are not just regular turtles. They have half human blood with the their already turtle blood. So technically they look exactly how they are supposed. This isn't a cartoon like the 2007 live action animated TMNT movie starring Patrick Stewart, Sara Geller, and Chris Evans. Live action is live action with real people doing the stunts not CARTOON!!!!!!!  I don't care what anyone says the 80s got the TMNT series all wrong. For 4 reasons 1. They made the Shredder act all wimpy. Through out the whole series plus the Foot soldiers and Kraang weren't any better.   2. The only turtle that the 80's and 90's tv shows and movies have ever gotten right was Michelangelo. The average teenager/surfer accent turtle of the group and the younger sibling.   3. They made the Shredder act all wimpy. Through out the whole series plus the Foot soldiers and Kraang weren't any better. What I just wrote for number 3. They screwed their voices up. Poorly...They give Leo too deep of a voice, they made Donnie act stupid and not knowing what he was doing, and Raph way to nice than he really is.  4. Raph is suppose to be the hot-head, over protective, jerk, and rude brother of the group. With a noticeable Brooklyn Accent. Picks fights with Leo and gives him a hard time about Leo being the leader. Even though he is those things he truly cares deeply for his family and friends even though he doesn't show it 24/7. Leo is the leader, older brother, has to keep an eye on his brothers especially Mikey, tries to keep is brothers out of trouble, and mature. He has a fear of losing his family and friends. He basically has to care the weight of the world on his shoulders. Donnie is the smart, genius, tech guy, and pathetic turtle of the brother. He doesn't like violence even though he fights the Foot, Purple Dragons, and other mutants. He isn't really into that unless he has to in order to protect his family, friends, and himself.   Then the reason why Peter Laird bought the copy rights to Venus De Milo who any barely knows about is because of the 90s TV Show TMNT The Next Mutation. The whole point of the show was supposed to be about Venus and centered around this mysterious female turtle who shows up in the first episode.   Reasons why Venus De Milo doesn't show up in any of the newer TMNT Series or Movies.   1. Her whole character it's self was horribly wrong. Why?  -Kevin Eastman the original creator of Venus De Milo's character, made her personality and general make-up to be closely similar to Leonardo.  -She is supposed to be mature.  -She's a complex character and the weapons the tessens were wrong for her character. Venus should have been using these weapons the katana and bow and arrows. They are for skilled hands. Which is what she is a skilled and complex character.  -She is a shinobi and she is mediating throughout every episode. She is more intoned with spiritual side of her. Which is how she able to channel her powers.   2. The season 1 was missed up horribly. Why?  -the title is called The Next Mutation. Mean when Venus shows up in the first episode to help the turtles. The episodes following, should have been centered around her character alone. Because we already know about the turtles and splinter. But we don't know anything about Venus other than she is a shinobi.  -Venus' dad is close friends with Splinter which both of them tell the turtles. That's basically all we know plus how did Venus gain these Shinobi powers. That wasn't ever talked about at all in the season. Which is really stupid. The only things we know about Venus is that she was mutated around the same time the turtles and splinter were mutated.  -There's no background about this strange shinobi turtle. How does that work to have a great character in your hands and not make the whole seasons about her.   3. The villains.  -The villains weren't the Purple Dragons, Foot, or Shredder except for the first episode.  -The Villains were all the foes of the Female turtle Venus who knew about them and weaknesses.  -Seriously, we knew more about foes of Venus De Milo than the actual main character herself.   That's why Peter Laird stopped production of this TV series and bought the copyrights to her. Because the people who were producing this series screwed it up. They weren't following Kevin Eastman's original ideas for Venus at all.   I'm so sick and tired of reading comments about how Michael Bay screws up the Transformers movies and now how he is screwing up TMNT. The critics need to do their research and read this book called the Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles: The Ulimate History which you can find at Barnes Noble. It talks about how Kevin Eastman and Peter Laird created TMNT to begin from the Comics to the 2014 movie. It was written by them with other people helping out.   If anyone should watch TMNT and know it better from the comics it's 2003-2007 animated series of TMNT. You can type in TMNT season 1 episode 1 Things Change and it's the only TV series that comes closest to Kevin and Peter's comic book.   Now about April O Neil's character. In the earlier comics in 1984 which was the year of when the first TMNT comic can out. April originally had black and brown hair in the comics. It wasn't until sometime in the 1990s comics when you were seeing April with red or orange hair. So Michael wasn't wrong about April's character. There are different story lines through the history of the comics about April. In one Casey and April weren't together. Yes, Casey had a daughter named Shadow who Mikey ends up having a love interest in Shadow.   There is some much that no one truly knows about the comics that have to relate to movies and the tv shows. Michael Bay made the turtles correct because I said this once but I'm saying it again. It's a LIVE ACTION FILM!!!!!!! People COME ON!!!!!! Really!!!!!!! Do I really need to spell it out for you all. *rolling my eyes and facepalming* You all don't know a damn thing about TMNT comics or TV series. I mean honestly. It drives me insane to read about this every damn time the man makes a film. He does do research about these cartoon series and if you all would watch the damn bonus features about how he makes his makes his movies you will see Kevin Eastman and Peter Laird talking about their thoughts towards Michael Bay's spin on THEIR turtle creation. Kevin Eastman and Peter Laird have told everyone a million times that the Turtles are HUMANOID!!!!! Meaning they are half human with their already turtle blood.
